                "solution": "To determine which of the professor's claims (C1) and (C2) follow from the given axioms (a) and (b), we analyze the structure of the binary operation $ * $ on the integers that satisfies:\n\n- **(a)** $ x * (x * y) = y $ for all $ x, y \\in \\mathbb{Z} $\n- **(b)** $ (x * y) * y = x $ for all $ x, y \\in \\mathbb{Z} $\n\n---\n\n### **Claim (C1): The operation $ * $ is commutative**\n\nWe aim to prove that for all $ x, y \\in \\mathbb{Z} $, we have:\n\n$$\nx * y = y * x\n$$\n\nLet\u2019s define:\n- $ A = x * y $\n- $ B = y * x $\n\nFrom **(a)**, we know:\n$$\nx * A = y \\quad \\text{and} \\quad y * B = x\n$$\n\nFrom **(b)**, we know:\n$$\nA * y = x \\quad \\text{and} \\quad B * x = y\n$$\n\nNow, observe that both $ x * A $ and $ B * x $ equal $ y $. That is:\n$$\nx * A = B * x\n$$\n\nThis is a key identity. Since the operation satisfies both **(a)** and **(b)**, we can derive a **cancellation law**:\n\n- **Right Cancellation:** If $ a * c = b * c $, then $ a = b $\n- **Left Cancellation:** If $ c * a = c * b $, then $ a = b $\n\nThese follow directly from **(a)** and **(b)** by applying them to the equality and using the uniqueness of the result.\n\nNow, returning to the identity:\n$$\nx * A = B * x\n$$\n\nWe can apply **right cancellation** to this equality. That is, since both sides are equal and the operation is on the right, we can cancel the $ x $ on the right-hand side, yielding:\n$$\nA = B\n$$\n\nTherefore:\n$$\nx * y = y * x\n$$\n\nThis proves that the operation $ * $ is **commutative**, so **(C1)** follows from the axioms.\n\n---\n\n### **Claim (C2): The operation $ * $ is associative**\n\nWe now examine whether the operation is associative, i.e., whether:\n$$\n(x * y) * z = x * (y * z) \\quad \\text{for all } x, y, z \\in \\mathbb{Z}\n$$\n\nTo test this, consider the following concrete example:\n\nDefine the operation $ * $ on $ \\mathbb{Z} $ as:\n$$\nx * y = c - x - y\n$$\nfor some fixed integer $ c $. This operation is well-defined on $ \\mathbb{Z} $.\n\nWe now verify that this operation satisfies both axioms:\n\n- **Axiom (a):**\n  $$\n  x * (x * y) = x * (c - x - y) = c - x - (c - x - y) = y\n  $$\n  So (a) is satisfied.\n\n- **Axiom (b):**\n  $$\n  (x * y) * y = (c - x - y) * y = c - (c - x - y) - y = x\n  $$\n  So (b) is satisfied.\n\nThis operation is **commutative**, since:\n$$\nx * y = c - x - y = c - y - x = y * x\n$$\n\nHowever, it is **not associative**. For example, take $ c = 0 $, so $ x * y = -x - y $. Then:\n$$\n(x * y) * z = (-x - y) * z = -(-x - y) - z = x + y - z\n$$\n$$\nx * (y * z) = x * (-y - z) = -x - (-y - z) = -x + y + z\n$$\n\nIn general, $ x + y - z \\neq -x + y + z $, so:\n$$\n(x * y) * z \\neq x * (y * z)\n$$\n\nThus, **(C2)** does **not** follow from the axioms.\n\n---\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nFrom the analysis:\n\n- **Claim (C1):** The operation $ * $ is commutative \u2014 this **does** follow from the axioms.\n- **Claim (C2):** The operation $ * $ is associative \u2014 this **does not** follow from the axioms.\n\n$$\n\\boxed{C1}\n$$",
