                "solution": "Here is a self\u2010contained proof that  \n\u2003(a) forces the unique form of \u201c\\(*\\)\u201d on \\(\\Bbb Z\\),  \n\u2003from which commutativity (C1) follows at once,  \n\u2003but associativity (C2) fails.  \n\nProof.  \nDefine, for each fixed \\(x\\in\\Bbb Z\\), the map  \n\\[\nf_x:\\Bbb Z\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\Bbb Z,\\qquad\nf_x(y)\\;=\\;x*y.\n\\]  \nThen axiom (a) says\n\\[\nx*(x*y)\\;=\\;y\n\\quad\\Longleftrightarrow\\quad\nf_x\\bigl(f_x(y)\\bigr)\\;=\\;y\n\\quad\\forall\\,y\\in\\Bbb Z.\n\\]\nHence \\(f_x\\circ f_x=\\id_{\\Bbb Z}\\).  In particular \\(f_x\\) is bijective (its own inverse).  \n\nDefine a new function  \n\\[\ng:\\Bbb Z\\times\\Bbb Z\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\Bbb Z\n\\quad\\text{by}\\quad\ng(x,y)\\;=\\;f_x(y)+y\\;=\\;x*y\\;+\\;y.\n\\]\nThen for every \\(x,y\\) we have\n\\[\ng\\bigl(x,f_x(y)\\bigr)\n=\\;f_x\\bigl(f_x(y)\\bigr)\\;+\\;f_x(y)\n=\\;y\\;+\\;f_x(y)\n=\\;g(x,y).\n\\]\nBut as \\(y\\) ranges over \\(\\Bbb Z\\), so does \\(f_x(y)\\) (surjectivity of \\(f_x\\)).  Thus for each fixed \\(x\\), the value of \n\\(\\;g(x,y)\\) cannot depend on \\(y\\).  \nHence there is a function \\(a:\\Bbb Z\\to\\Bbb Z\\) so that\n\\[\ng(x,y)\\;=\\;a(x)\n\\quad\\Longleftrightarrow\\quad\nx*y\\;+\\;y\\;=\\;a(x)\n\\quad\\Longleftrightarrow\\quad\nx*y\\;=\\;a(x)\\;-\\;y.\n\\]\nIn other words, for each \\(x\\) there is an integer \\(a(x)\\) so that\n\\[\n\\boxed{\n\\forall\\,x,y,\\qquad\nx*y \\;=\\;a(x)\\;-\\;y.\n}\n\\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nNext we impose axiom (b):  \n\\[\n(x*y)*y \\;=\\;x.\n\\]\nBy \\((1)\\), the left\u2013hand side is\n\\[\n(x*y)*y\n=\\;a\\bigl(x*y\\bigr)\\;-\\;y\n=\\;a\\bigl(a(x)-y\\bigr)\\;-\\;y,\n\\]\nso \\((b)\\) becomes\n\\[\na\\bigl(a(x)-y\\bigr)\\;-\\;y \\;=\\;x\n\\quad\\Longleftrightarrow\\quad\na\\bigl(a(x)-y\\bigr)\\;=\\;x+y.\n\\]\nNow set\n\\[\nu\\;=\\;a(x)-y.\n\\]\nSince \\(y\\) was arbitrary, so is \\(u\\).  The displayed equation says\n\\[\n\\forall\\,x,u,\\quad\na(u)\\;=\\;x+y\n\\quad\\text{where }u=a(x)-y.\n\\]\nBut \\(y=a(x)-u\\), so\n\\[\na(u)\\;=\\;x + \\bigl(a(x)-u\\bigr)\n\\;=\\;\\bigl[a(x)+x\\bigr]\\;-\\;u.\n\\]\nIn particular the quantity\n\\[\na(u)+u \\;=\\; a(x)+x\n\\]\nis independent of both \\(u\\) and \\(x\\).  Call that common constant \\(C\\).  Thus\n\\[\na(x)+x\\;=\\;C\n\\quad\\Longrightarrow\\quad\na(x)\\;=\\;C - x.\n\\]\nSubstituting back into \\((1)\\) gives the only possible formula for \u201c\\(*\\)\u201d:\n\\[\n\\boxed{\n\\forall\\,x,y\\in\\Bbb Z,\n\\qquad\nx*y \\;=\\;a(x)-y\n\\;=\\;(C-x)-y\n\\;=\\;C \\;-\\;x \\;-\\;y.\n}\n\\tag{2}\n\\]\nIn particular\n\\[\nx*y = C - x - y = C - y - x = y*x,\n\\]\nso \\(*\\) is commutative.  This proves that under (a),(b) the operation \\(*\\) must be commutative\u2014i.e.\\ (C1) follows.\n\nFinally we check associativity.  Using \\((2)\\) one computes:\n\\[\n(x*y)*z\n=\\bigl(C-x-y\\bigr)*z\n=\\;C \\;-\\;(C-x-y)\\;-\\;z\n=\\;x+y-z,\n\\]\nwhereas\n\\[\nx*(y*z)\n=\\;x*\\bigl(C-y-z\\bigr)\n=\\;C\\;-\\;x\\;-\\;(C-y-z)\n=\\;y+z-x.\n\\]\nThese two are equal for all \\(x,y,z\\) only if\n\\[\nx+y-z \\;=\\;y+z-x\n\\quad\\Longleftrightarrow\\quad\n2x=2z\n\\]\nfor all \\(x,z\\), which is false in \\(\\Bbb Z\\).  Hence \\(*\\) is not associative.  Thus (C2) does not follow from the axioms.\n\nSummary.  From axioms  \n\u2003(a) \\(x*(x*y)=y\\) and  \n\u2003(b) \\((x*y)*y=x\\)  \none deduces the unique form  \n\\[\nx*y \\;=\\;C - x - y,\n\\]\nwhich is manifestly commutative but fails associativity.  Therefore\n\n\u2013 (C1) commutativity follows,  \n\u2013 (C2) associativity does not.  \n\u220e",
