                "solution": "Here is a self\u2013contained proof that no \u201cvery convex\u2019\u2019 function can exist.  We follow the convention that all functions \\(f\\colon\\Bbb R\\to\\Bbb R\\) are real-valued (never \\(+\\infty\\) or \\(-\\infty\\)).  \n\n**Definition.**  We call \\(f\\) *very convex* if for all \\(x,y\\in\\Bbb R\\),\n\\[\n\\frac{f(x)+f(y)}{2}\\;\\ge\\;f\\!\\Bigl(\\frac{x+y}{2}\\Bigr)\\;+\\;|x-y|\\,.\n\\tag{V}\n\\]\n\nWe shall assume, for sake of contradiction, that there *is* a very-convex \\(f\\), and deduce an impossibility.\n\n---\n\n**1. Midpoint\u2010convexity and continuity.**  \n\nFrom \\((V)\\) we immediately get the usual midpoint\u2010convex inequality\n\\[\nf\\!\\Bigl(\\frac{x+y}{2}\\Bigr)\\;\\le\\;\\frac{f(x)+f(y)}{2},\n\\]\nso \\(f\\) is midpoint\u2010convex.  A standard fact in real analysis is\n\n\u2003\u2022 A midpoint\u2010convex function \\(f\\colon\\Bbb R\\to\\Bbb R\\) which is continuous at one point is in fact convex on all of \\(\\Bbb R\\).  \n\nWe will prove continuity of \\(f\\) at an arbitrary point \\(x_0\\), thus showing \\(f\\) is truly convex.\n\nFix any \\(x_0\\in\\Bbb R\\) and any \\(\\varepsilon>0\\).  Define\n\\[\n\\delta_k \\;=\\;\\frac\\varepsilon{2^k},\n\\quad\ns_k \\;=\\;\\frac{f(x_0+\\delta_k)\\;-\\;f(x_0)}{\\delta_k}\n\\quad(k=0,1,2,\\dots).\n\\]\nWe first show \\(s_k\\to0\\) in such a way that \\(f(x_0+\\delta_k)\\to f(x_0)\\).\n\nApply the very\u2010convexity \\((V)\\) with\n\\[\nx=x_0+\\delta_k,\\quad y=x_0+2\\,\\delta_k.\n\\]\nThen \\(\\tfrac{x+y}{2}=x_0+\\delta_k\\), \\(|x-y|=2\\delta_k\\), and\n\\[\n\\frac{f(x_0+\\delta_k)+f(x_0+2\\delta_k)}{2}\n\\;\\ge\\;\nf\\!\\bigl(x_0+\\delta_k\\bigr)\\;+\\;2\\delta_k.\n\\]\nRearrange:\n\\[\nf(x_0+2\\delta_k)\\;-\\;f(x_0+\\delta_k)\n\\;\\ge\\;2\\,\\bigl(\\,f(x_0+\\delta_k)-f(x_0)\\bigr)\n\\;+\\;4\\,\\delta_k.\n\\]\nDivide through by \\(2\\delta_k\\):\n\\[\n\\frac{f(x_0+2\\delta_k)-f(x_0+\\delta_k)}{2\\delta_k}\n\\;\\ge\\;\n\\frac{f(x_0+\\delta_k)-f(x_0)}{\\delta_k}\\;+\\;2\n\\;\\Longrightarrow\\;\ns_{\\,k+1}\\;\\le\\;s_k\\;-\\;2.\n\\]\nBy induction,\n\\[\ns_k\\;\\le\\;s_0\\;-\\;2k,\n\\qquad k=0,1,2,\\dots\n\\]\nHence\n\\[\n0\\;\\le\\;f(x_0+\\delta_k)-f(x_0)\n\\;=\\;\\delta_k\\,s_k\n\\;\\le\\;\n\\delta_k\\bigl(s_0-2k\\bigr)\n\\;=\\;\n\\frac\\varepsilon{2^k}\\,(s_0-2k).\n\\]\nBut \\(\\tfrac\\varepsilon{2^k}(s_0-2k)\\to0\\) as \\(k\\to\\infty\\).  Thus\n\\[\nf(x_0+\\delta_k)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;f(x_0).\n\\]\nA completely analogous argument on the left shows\n\\(f(x_0-\\delta_k)\\to f(x_0)\\).  Therefore \\(f\\) is continuous at \\(x_0\\).  Since \\(x_0\\) was arbitrary, \\(f\\) is continuous everywhere.\n\nBy the standard theorem (e.g.\\ in any real\u2010analysis text) that a continuous midpoint\u2010convex function on \\(\\Bbb R\\) is in fact convex, we conclude\n\n\u2003\u2022 **\\(f\\) is convex on \\(\\Bbb R\\).**\n\n---\n\n**2. Secant\u2010slopes of a convex function are bounded.**  \n\nFor a convex function \\(f\\) and any fixed \\(x\\), define the *secant slope*\n\\[\ns(h)\\;=\\;\\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h},\n\\qquad h>0.\n\\]\nIt is well\u2010known and elementary that for convex \\(f\\),\n\n(i)  if \\(0<h'<h\\), then\n\\[\n\\frac{f(x+h')-f(x)}{h'}\\;\\le\\;\\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h},\n\\]\nso \\(h\\mapsto s(h)\\) is nonincreasing;\n\n(ii) for any fixed \\(H>0\\),\n\\(\ns(h)\\le \\frac{f(x+H)-f(x)}{H}\n\\)\nfor all \\(0<h\\le H\\), and\n\\(\ns(h)\\ge \\frac{f(x)-f(x-H)}{H}\n\\)\nfor all \\(0<h\\le H\\).\nHence on \\(0<h\\le H\\), \\(s(h)\\) is trapped between two finite bounds and therefore\n\\[\n\\lim_{h\\to0^+}s(h)\n\\]\nexists *and is finite*.  That limit is nothing but the right\u2010derivative \\(f'_+(x)\\).\n\n---\n\n**3. The final contradiction.**  \n\nOn the other hand, from the very\u2010convexity hypothesis \\((V)\\) applied to\n\\[\nx\\mapsto x,\n\\quad\ny\\mapsto x+2h,\n\\]\none obtains exactly as above\n\\[\ns(h/2)\\;\\le\\;s(h)\\;-\\;2,\n\\qquad\\forall\\,h>0.\n\\]\nBut convexity forces \\(s(h/2)\\ge s(h)\\).  Hence\n\\[\ns(h)\\;\\le\\;s(h)\\;-\\;2\n\\quad\\Longrightarrow\\quad\n0\\le -2,\n\\]\na manifest contradiction.\n\n---\n\nSince the sole assumption\u2014that \\(f\\) satisfies the \u201cvery convex\u2019\u2019 inequality \\((V)\\)\u2014leads to an impossibility, **no** real\u2010valued function can satisfy \\((V)\\) for *every* \\(x,y\\in\\Bbb R\\).  This completes the proof.  \u220e",
