                "solution": "Assume, for the sake of contradiction, that a real-valued function  \n\n\\[\nf:\\mathbb R\\longrightarrow\\mathbb R\n\\]\n\nsatisfies  \n\\[\n\\frac{f(x)+f(y)}{2}\\;\\ge\\;f\\!\\left(\\frac{x+y}{2}\\right)+|x-y|\n\\qquad\\text{for all }x,y\\in\\mathbb R.\n\\tag{1}\n\\]\n\nThroughout the proof we shall use the equivalent form obtained from (1) by multiplying by \\(2\\):\n\n\\[\nf(x)+f(y)\\;\\ge\\;2f\\!\\left(\\frac{x+y}{2}\\right)+2|x-y|.\n\\tag{2}\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nStep 1.  Three inequalities involving the points \\(-1,0,1\\).\n\nChoose in (2)\n\n\u2022 \\(x=1,\\;y=-1\\).  \nThen \\(\\dfrac{x+y}{2}=0\\) and \\(|x-y|=2\\); hence  \n\\[\nf(1)+f(-1)\\;\\ge\\;2f(0)+4.\n\\tag{3}\n\\]\n\n\u2022 \\(x=1,\\;y=0\\).  \nThen \\(\\dfrac{x+y}{2}=\\tfrac12\\) and \\(|x-y|=1\\); hence  \n\\[\nf(1)+f(0)\\;\\ge\\;2f\\!\\left(\\frac12\\right)+2.\n\\tag{4}\n\\]\n\n\u2022 \\(x=0,\\;y=-1\\).  \nThen \\(\\dfrac{x+y}{2}=-\\tfrac12\\) and \\(|x-y|=1\\); hence  \n\\[\nf(0)+f(-1)\\;\\ge\\;2f\\!\\left(-\\frac12\\right)+2.\n\\tag{5}\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nStep 2.  A bound for \\(f\\!\\left(\\tfrac12\\right)+f\\!\\left(-\\tfrac12\\right)\\).\n\nAdd (4) and (5):\n\n\\[\nf(1)+2f(0)+f(-1)\\;\\ge\\;2f\\!\\left(\\frac12\\right)+2f\\!\\left(-\\frac12\\right)+4.\n\\tag{6}\n\\]\n\nNow subtract (3) from (6); on the left-hand side the terms \\(f(1)+f(-1)\\) cancel, leaving \\(2f(0)\\):\n\n\\[\n2f(0)\\;\\ge\\;2f\\!\\left(\\frac12\\right)+2f\\!\\left(-\\frac12\\right)-2f(0).\n\\]\n\nDivide by \\(2\\):\n\n\\[\n2f(0)\\;\\ge\\;f\\!\\left(\\tfrac12\\right)+f\\!\\left(-\\tfrac12\\right).\n\\tag{7}\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nStep 3.  A contradictory reverse inequality.\n\nApply (2) once more with \\(x=\\tfrac12,\\;y=-\\tfrac12\\).\nHere \\(\\dfrac{x+y}{2}=0\\) and \\(|x-y|=1\\); therefore\n\n\\[\nf\\!\\left(\\tfrac12\\right)+f\\!\\left(-\\tfrac12\\right)\\;\\ge\\;2f(0)+2.\n\\tag{8}\n\\]\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nStep 4.  Contradiction.\n\nInequalities (7) and (8) give\n\n\\[\n2f(0)\\;\\ge\\;f\\!\\left(\\tfrac12\\right)+f\\!\\left(-\\tfrac12\\right)\\;\\ge\\;2f(0)+2,\n\\]\n\nwhich is impossible.  Hence our initial assumption was false.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nConclusion.  \nNo real-valued function can satisfy (1); in other words, a \u201cvery convex\u2019\u2019 function does not exist.",
