                "solution": "To prove that **no very convex function exists**, we begin by analyzing the inequality that defines such a function:\n\n$$\n\\frac{f(x) + f(y)}{2} \\geq f\\left(\\frac{x + y}{2}\\right) + |x - y| \\quad \\text{for all } x, y \\in \\mathbb{R}.\n$$\n\nThis inequality is stronger than the standard definition of convexity, which requires:\n\n$$\n\\frac{f(x) + f(y)}{2} \\geq f\\left(\\frac{x + y}{2}\\right).\n$$\n\nHere, the right-hand side includes an additional term $ |x - y| $, making the inequality more restrictive. Our goal is to show that **no real-valued function** can satisfy this inequality for all real $ x $ and $ y $.\n\n---\n\n### Step 1: Reformulating the Inequality\n\nLet us define a new variable $ z = \\frac{x + y}{2} $, and let $ t = \\frac{|x - y|}{2} $. Then we can write:\n\n$$\nx = z - t, \\quad y = z + t.\n$$\n\nSubstituting into the inequality, we get:\n\n$$\n\\frac{f(z - t) + f(z + t)}{2} \\geq f(z) + 2t.\n$$\n\nMultiplying both sides by 2:\n\n$$\nf(z - t) + f(z + t) - 2f(z) \\geq 4t.\n$$\n\nDefine the function:\n\n$$\n\\psi(t) = f(z - t) + f(z + t) - 2f(z).\n$$\n\nThen the inequality becomes:\n\n$$\n\\psi(t) \\geq 4t \\quad \\text{for all } t \\geq 0.\n$$\n\nThis must hold for **all real numbers** $ z $ and $ t \\geq 0 $.\n\n---\n\n### Step 2: Recursive Application of the Inequality\n\nWe now analyze the behavior of $ \\psi(t) $ by applying the inequality recursively. Consider:\n\n$$\n\\psi(t) = f(z - t) + f(z + t) - 2f(z).\n$$\n\nWe can apply the same inequality to $ t/2 $:\n\n$$\n\\psi(t/2) \\geq 4 \\cdot \\frac{t}{2} = 2t.\n$$\n\nNow, consider the inequality for $ t $ and $ t/2 $:\n\nFrom the original inequality:\n\n$$\n\\frac{f(z) + f(z + t)}{2} \\geq f(z + t/2) + t,\n$$\n$$\n\\frac{f(z) + f(z - t)}{2} \\geq f(z - t/2) + t.\n$$\n\nAdding both inequalities:\n\n$$\n\\frac{f(z + t) + f(z - t) + 2f(z)}{2} \\geq f(z + t/2) + f(z - t/2) + 2t.\n$$\n\nRewriting:\n\n$$\nf(z + t) + f(z - t) \\geq 2f(z) + 2f(z + t/2) + 2f(z - t/2) + 4t.\n$$\n\nSubtracting $ 2f(z) $ from both sides:\n\n$$\n\\psi(t) \\geq \\psi(t/2) + 4t.\n$$\n\nThis is a **recursive inequality**. Using this, we can derive a sequence of lower bounds for $ \\psi(t) $:\n\n- From the original inequality: $ \\psi(t) \\geq 4t $\n- From the recursion: $ \\psi(t) \\geq \\psi(t/2) + 4t \\geq 4 \\cdot \\frac{t}{2} + 4t = 6t $\n- Applying again: $ \\psi(t) \\geq \\psi(t/4) + 4t \\geq 4 \\cdot \\frac{t}{4} + 4t = 5t $\n- Continuing this process, we find that $ \\psi(t) \\geq 4(n + 1)t $ for all $ n \\in \\mathbb{N} $\n\n---\n\n### Step 3: Deriving a Contradiction\n\nFrom the recursive inequality, we see that for any fixed $ t > 0 $, the lower bound on $ \\psi(t) $ increases without bound as $ n \\to \\infty $. That is:\n\n$$\n\\psi(t) \\geq 4(n + 1)t \\quad \\text{for all } n \\in \\mathbb{N}.\n$$\n\nThis implies that $ \\psi(t) $ must be **infinite** for all $ t > 0 $, which is a contradiction because $ \\psi(t) = f(z - t) + f(z + t) - 2f(z) $ is a finite expression for any real-valued function $ f $.\n\n---\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe recursive application of the inequality leads to an unbounded lower bound on $ \\psi(t) $, which contradicts the assumption that $ f $ is a real-valued function. Therefore, **no function** $ f: \\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R} $ can satisfy the inequality:\n\n$$\n\\frac{f(x) + f(y)}{2} \\geq f\\left(\\frac{x + y}{2}\\right) + |x - y| \\quad \\text{for all } x, y \\in \\mathbb{R}.\n$$\n\n---\n\n### Final Answer\n\n$$\n\\boxed{\\text{No such very convex function exists.}}\n$$",
