                "solution": "Here is a self\u2013contained proof.  \n\n**Proof.**  Label the chairs by positions \\(1,2,\\dots,16\\).  We identify any choice of 8 chairs with a binary string of length 16 having exactly eight \u201c1\u201d\u2019s (chosen chairs) and eight \u201c0\u201d\u2019s (empty chairs).  The condition \u201cno person sits next to two other people\u201d means exactly that there is no block of three consecutive chosen chairs, i.e. the string contains no substring \\(\\,\\mathtt{111}\\).  Equivalently, every maximal run of consecutive \u201c1\u201d\u2019s has length at most 2.  \n\nWe now count the number of binary strings of length 16 with exactly eight 1\u2019s, no run of three 1\u2019s, by breaking them into runs of 1\u2019s separated by runs of 0\u2019s.  \n\n1.  Let the total number of runs of 1\u2019s be \\(r\\).  Since each run has length either 1 or 2, write\n   \\[\n     x = \\bigl(\\text{number of runs of length }2\\bigr), \n     \\quad\n     y = \\bigl(\\text{number of runs of length }1\\bigr).\n   \\]\n   Then\n   \\[\n     2x + 1\\cdot y = 8\n     \\quad\\text{and}\\quad\n     r = x + y.\n   \\]\n   Hence \\(y = 8-2x\\) and\n   \\[\n     r = x + (8-2x) = 8 - x.\n   \\]\n   Since \\(y\\ge0\\), we have \\(8-2x\\ge0\\), i.e.\\ \\(0\\le x\\le4\\).  \n\n2.  There are \\(\\displaystyle \\binom{r}{x}\\) ways to choose which \\(x\\) of the \\(r\\) runs have length 2 (the other \\(r-x\\) runs then have length 1).  \n\n3.  Between these runs of 1\u2019s we must place the eight 0\u2019s so that no two runs of 1\u2019s become adjacent.  Concretely, if we write the runs of 1\u2019s in order\n   \\[\n     R_1,\\;R_2,\\;\\dots,\\;R_r,\n   \\]\n   then we place some (possibly zero) 0\u2019s before \\(R_1\\), some (at least one) between \\(R_1\\) and \\(R_2\\), \u2026, at least one between \\(R_{r-1}\\) and \\(R_r\\), and some (possibly zero) after \\(R_r\\).  Let\n   \\[\n     z_0 = \\#\\{0\\hbox{\u2019s before }R_1\\},\\quad\n     z_i = \\#\\{0\\hbox{\u2019s between }R_i\\text{ and }R_{i+1}\\}\\,(1\\le i\\le r-1),\\quad\n     z_r = \\#\\{0\\hbox{\u2019s after }R_r\\}.\n   \\]\n   Then\n   \\[\n     z_0 + z_1 + \\cdots + z_r = 8,\n     \\quad\n     z_1,\\dots,z_{r-1}\\ge1,\n     \\quad\n     z_0,z_r\\ge0.\n   \\]\n   Make the substitution\n   \\[\n     t_i = \n     \\begin{cases}\n       z_i - 1, & 1\\le i\\le r-1,\\\\\n       z_i,     & i=0\\text{ or }i=r,\n     \\end{cases}\n   \\]\n   so that each \\(t_i\\ge0\\) and\n   \\[\n     (z_0) + (z_1-1) + \\cdots + (z_{r-1}-1) + (z_r)\n     = 8 - (r-1).\n   \\]\n   Hence\n   \\[\n     t_0 + t_1 + \\cdots + t_r \\;=\\; 8 - (r-1) \\;=\\; 9 - r.\n   \\]\n   By the standard \u201cstars and bars\u201d lemma, the number of nonnegative\u2013 integer solutions to\n   \\(\\;t_0+\\cdots+t_r = 9-r\\)\n   is\n   \\[\n     \\binom{(9-r)+(r+1)-1}{(r+1)-1}\n     \\;=\\;\n     \\binom{9}{r}.\n   \\]\n\n4.  Putting it all together:  for each \\(x=0,1,2,3,4\\) we have\n   \\[\n     r = 8 - x,\n   \\]\n   and the number of strings with exactly \\(x\\) runs of length 2 (and hence \\(r\\) runs total) is\n   \\[\n     \\binom{r}{x}\\,\\times\\,\\binom{9}{r}\n     \\;=\\;\n     \\binom{8-x}{x}\\,\\binom{9}{8-x}.\n   \\]\n   Therefore the total number \\(N\\) of valid choices is\n   \\[\n     N\n     \\;=\\;\n     \\sum_{x=0}^4\n     \\binom{8-x}{x}\\,\\binom{9}{8-x}.\n   \\]\n   We compute term by term:\n   \\[\n     \\begin{aligned}\n       x=0:&\\quad \\binom{8}{0}\\binom{9}{8}=1\\cdot9=9,\\\\\n       x=1:&\\quad \\binom{7}{1}\\binom{9}{7}=7\\cdot36=252,\\\\\n       x=2:&\\quad \\binom{6}{2}\\binom{9}{6}=15\\cdot84=1260,\\\\\n       x=3:&\\quad \\binom{5}{3}\\binom{9}{5}=10\\cdot126=1260,\\\\\n       x=4:&\\quad \\binom{4}{4}\\binom{9}{4}=1\\cdot126=126.\n     \\end{aligned}\n   \\]\n   Summing,\n   \\[\n     N = 9 + 252 + 1260 + 1260 + 126 = 2907.\n   \\]\n   Hence the remainder when \\(N\\) is divided by 1000 is\n   \\[\n     2907 \\equiv 907 \\pmod{1000}.\n   \\]\n\nTherefore the desired remainder is \n\\[\n\\boxed{907}.\n\\]",
