                "solution": "Let  \n\np(x)= (x-m\u2081)(x-m\u2082)(x-m\u2083)(x-m\u2084)(x-m\u2085) ,\u2003m\u2081 ,\u2026, m\u2085  distinct integers,  \n\nand let  \n\np(x)=x\u2075- e\u2081x\u2074+e\u2082x\u00b3- e\u2083x\u00b2+e\u2084x- e\u2085                                    (1)\n\nbe its expansion.  \n(The e\u1d62 are the elementary symmetric functions of the roots:\n e\u2081=\u2211m\u1d62 , e\u2082=\u2211m\u1d62m\u2c7c (i<j), \u2026 , e\u2085=m\u2081m\u2082m\u2083m\u2084m\u2085.)\n\nFor every i, e\u1d62 is an integer, so the number of non\u2013zero coefficients of p\nequals the number of non\u2013zero e\u1d62 (0\u2264i\u22645).\nOur task is to minimise this number.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n1.  A polynomial with only one non\u2013zero coefficient is impossible\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nBecause p is monic, p can have a single non\u2013zero coefficient only when  \n\np(x)=x\u2075 .\n\nBut x\u2075 has the single root 0 of multiplicity 5, whereas we require\nfive distinct integer roots.  Hence k\u22601.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n2.  Two non\u2013zero coefficients are impossible\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nAssume p has exactly two non\u2013zero coefficients.  Then for some integer\nc\u22600 and some exponent k with 0\u2264k\u22644\n\np(x)=x\u2075+cx\u1d4f .                                                     (2)\n\nWe distinguish the five possible values of k.\n\n\u2022  k=4.  Then p(x)=x\u2075+cx\u2074=x\u2074(x+c).  \n   The factor x\u2074 gives the root 0 with multiplicity 4, contradicting\n   distinctness.\n\n\u2022  k=3.  p(x)=x\u2075+cx\u00b3=x\u00b3(x\u00b2+c) again gives 0 with multiplicity 3.\n\n\u2022  k=2.  p(x)=x\u2075+cx\u00b2=x\u00b2(x\u00b3+c) gives 0 with multiplicity 2.\n\nIn all three cases we already have a repeated root, so k cannot be 2,3,4.\n\n\u2022  k=0.  p(x)=x\u2075+c.  Any integer root r must satisfy r\u2075=-c,\n   so at most one integer root exists.\n   Five distinct integer roots are therefore impossible.\n\n\u2022  k=1.  p(x)=x\u2075+cx=x(x\u2074+c).  \n   One root is 0.  The remaining four roots must\n   satisfy x\u2074=-c, i.e. x\u2074 is the same fixed integer for all of them.\n   For integers, this forces each root to be \u00b1d with d\u2074=-c.  Hence\n   among the four numbers there are at most two different values (d and \u2013d),\n   so together with 0 we obtain at most three distinct roots \u2013 not five.\n\nSince none of the five sub-cases is possible, no polynomial\nwith exactly two non\u2013zero coefficients can have five distinct integer\nzeros.  Therefore k\u22602.\n\nConsequently every admissible p must contain at least three non\u2013zero\ncoefficients:\n\nk \u2265 3.                                                           (3)\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n3.  A polynomial with exactly three non\u2013zero coefficients exists\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nConsider the five integers\n\nm\u2081=-2 ,\u2003m\u2082=-1 ,\u2003m\u2083=0 ,\u2003m\u2084=1 ,\u2003m\u2085=2 .\n\nAll are distinct.  Compute\n\np(x)=(x+2)(x+1)x(x-1)(x-2)\n     =x(x\u00b2-1)(x\u00b2-4)\n     =x(x\u2074-5x\u00b2+4)\n     =x\u2075-5x\u00b3+4x.                                                 (4)\n\nThe expansion (4) contains exactly three non\u2013zero coefficients\n(the coefficients of x\u2075, x\u00b3 and x), so for these roots we have k=3.\nBy (3) no smaller k is possible, hence\n\n\u2003\u2003k_min = 3,\n\nand the minimum is attained, for example, for\n\n{m\u2081,m\u2082,m\u2083,m\u2084,m\u2085}= {-2,-1,0,1,2} .\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n4.  Conclusion\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n1.  k=1 is impossible because x\u2075 has a multiple root.  \n2.  k=2 is impossible by the case-by-case discussion of (2).  \n3.  k=3 is attainable, as shown in (4).\n\nTherefore the smallest possible number of non-zero coefficients is\n\nk = 3,\n\nand one set of distinct integers that realises this minimum is\n\n{-2,-1,0,1,2}.",
